**Learning with AI Assisted Tools**

**Understanding Chunking**

The first codification was much harder to remember because it displayed 10 separate and independent symbols. Unless you made any effort to organize/connect those elements, your memory system was probably overloaded\!

During the second trial, your brain chunked the information into a meaningful and logical pattern: a phone-like dial. Your brain created a chunk based on what you previously knew to simplify the task.

So, chunking doesn’t mean grouping elements. It means actively connecting knowledge into patterns or clusters based on previous knowledge.

The information itself does not contain chunks: You build them yourself.

**Writing good prompts**

![image][image2]

I. Give Context When you describe the what, why or who before stating your intention, the AI generative tool will have more inputs/parameters to produce a suitable answer II. State a Specific Intention Define what you need and formulate a concrete/precise prompt. III. Interact With The Output The best way to interact with generative AI tools is to have a conversation with them in natural language.

After you get a response, make sure to talk\!

Ask for clarification 1\. Make a counterargument 2\. Go deeper on \[some\] part of the response 3\. Challenge any response that seems illogical

**Note-taking Approaches**

There are two ways of taking notes: passive and active. The first consists of repeating or reproducing the information you read. This approach is less effective for deep learning.

In contrast, the active approach focuses on elaborating the information to recreate it and make it yours. This includes activities such as:

1. Chunking knowledge

2. Finding by yourself examples or analogies

3. Connecting concepts with other domains you previously know

4. Formulating questions while you read

5. Writing down personal comments

6. Analyze the following three popular methods for taking notes and choose—or adapt\!—the one that suits you the best.

**Prompts to Apply**

AI generative tools can create opportunities to apply those concepts and skills you expect to learn. Here is a list of useful base prompts to retrieve and get feedback for your answers:

Self-testing for concepts: Create five closed-ended questions to test my knowledge about \[\]. Create five open-ended questions to assess the basic concepts behind \[\]. Give me a case analysis and three questions regarding that case to evaluate my understanding of \[\]. Please evaluate the following definition: \[“ “\]. Based on the official documentation, how accurate is it? Play as an interviewer from a big tech company. Present questions one by one regarding the concept \[\] I will explain \[\] concept and you will be a proffesor from a top university. Listen to and ask me questions while I explain the concept.

Practicing skills: Practicing: Design a step-by-step practice exercise to help master the commands for directory management in Linux. Can you create some exercises to practice \[\]? Provide a practice exercise for applying \[\]. Play as an interviewer from a big tech company. Create one practical exercise to test \[\] Getting feedback: Based on these parameters/criteria \[…\], evaluate the following piece of code. How can this piece of code be improved? What best practices can I apply to improve this \[\]? Play as a Java \[or any other technology\] mentor and provide feedback to the following solutions \[…\].
